05428nam a22009495i 9780520927087DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20012001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696770  a97805209270877 a10.1525/97805209270872doi  a(DE-B1597)520533  a(OCoLC)859389057  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aRA418.5.P6 4aRA418.5.P6 F37 2001eb 7aMED0000002bisacsh04a306.4/612231 aFarmer, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInfections and Inequalities :bThe Modern Plagues /cPaul Farmer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (424 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface To The Paperback Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Vitality Of Practice: On Personal Trajectories -- t2. Rethinking "Emerging Infectious Diseases" -- t3. Invisible Women: Class, Gender, And Hiv -- t4. The Exotic And The Mundane: Human Immunodeficiency Virus In The Caribbean -- t5. Culture, Poverty, And Hiv Transmission: The Case Of Rural Haiti -- tMiracles And Misery: An Ethnographic Interlude -- t6. Sending Sickness: Sorcery, Politics, And Changing Concepts Of Aids In Rural Haiti -- t7. The Consumption Of The Poor: Tuberculosis In The Late Twentieth Century -- t8. Optimism And Pessimism In Tuberculosis Control: Lessons From Rural Haiti -- t9. Immodest Claims Of Causality: Social Scientists And The "New" Tuberculosis -- t10. The Persistent Plagues: Biological Expressions Of Social Inequalities -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPaul Farmer has battled AIDS in rural Haiti and deadly strains of drug-resistant tuberculosis in the slums of Peru. A physician-anthropologist with more than fifteen years in the field, Farmer writes from the front lines of the war against these modern plagues and shows why, even more than those of history, they target the poor. This "peculiarly modern inequality" that permeates AIDS, TB, malaria, and typhoid in the modern world, and that feeds emerging (or re-emerging) infectious diseases such as Ebola and cholera, is laid bare in Farmer's harrowing stories of sickness and suffering.Challenging the accepted methodologies of epidemiology and international health, he points out that most current explanatory strategies, from "cost-effectiveness" to patient "noncompliance," inevitably lead to blaming the victims. In reality, larger forces, global as well as local, determine why some people are sick and others are shielded from risk. Yet this moving account is far from a hopeless inventory of insoluble problems. Farmer writes of what can be done in the face of seemingly overwhelming odds, by physicians determined to treat those in need. Infections and Inequalities weds meticulous scholarship with a passion for solutions—remedies for the plagues of the poor and the social maladies that have sustained them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunicable diseasesxSocial aspects. 0aPeople with social disabilitiesxHealth and hygiene. 0aPoorxHealth and hygiene. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  aaids.  abiography.  acancer.  acholera.  acost-effective treatment.  adisease.  adoctor autobiography.  adoctors without borders.  adrug-resistant tuberculosis.  aebola.  aepidemiology.  aherd immunity.  ahuman suffering.  aillness.  aintegrity research board.  ainternational health.  airb.  amedical anthropology.  amedical students.  amemoir.  anew methods.  anoncompliance.  apathology.  aphysician anthropologist.  aplague.  arevolutionary treatment.  ascholarship.  astories about diseases.  avaccinatio